    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#paci1996"/> (ph.)<citedRange/></bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>46.2214</citedRange></bibl>; 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#criscuolo2001b"/><citedRange/></bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>51.2213</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>084300</citedRange></bibl>.
                Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#caputo1954"/>, p. <citedRange>66, footnote 7</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><w lemma="βασιλεύς">Βασιλέα</w> <persName type="ruler" key="Ptolemy VI"><name nymRef="#Πτολεμαῖος">Πτο<supplied reason="lost">λεμαῖον</supplied></name> <rs type="epithet" key="Theos Philometor"><w lemma="θεός"><supplied reason="lost">θεὸν</supplied></w>
                    <lb n="2"/><w lemma="φιλομήτωρ">Φιλομήτορα</w></rs></persName> τ<supplied reason="lost">ὸν</supplied> <persName type="ruler" key="Ptolemy V and Cleopatra I"><persName type="ruler" key="Ptolemy V"><name nymRef="#Πτολεμαῖος"><supplied reason="lost">Πτολεμαίου</supplied></name></persName>
                    <lb n="3"/>καὶ <persName type="ruler" key="Cleopatra I"><name nymRef="#Κλεοπάτρα">Κλεοπάτρας</name></persName> <rs type="epithet" key="Theoi Epiphaneis"><w lemma="θεός"><supplied reason="lost">θεῶν</supplied></w> 
                        <w lemma="ἐπιφανής"><supplied reason="lost">Ἐπιφανῶν</supplied></w></rs></persName>
                    <lb n="4"/><space quantity="7" unit="character"/> ἡ <w>πόλις</w> <supplied reason="lost"><space quantity="7" unit="character"/></supplied>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p>
                    <app loc="2"><lem resp="#criscuolo2001b">Φιλομήτορα τ<supplied reason="lost">ὸν Πτολεμαίου</supplied></lem>
                        <rdg resp="#paci1996">Φιλομήτορα Π<supplied reason="lost">τολεμαίου</supplied></rdg>   
                    </app>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <app loc="3"><lem resp="#criscuolo2001b"><supplied reason="lost">θεῶν Ἐπιφανῶν</supplied></lem>
                        <rdg resp="#paci1996"><supplied reason="lost">ἀδελφόν</supplied></rdg>
                    </app>
               </p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p><supplied reason="subaudible">La statue</supplied> du roi Ptolémée, Dieu Philomètôr, fils de Ptolémée et Cléopatre, Dieux Epiphanes, 
                <supplied reason="subaudible">a été consacrée</supplied>, par la cité.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p><supplied reason="subaudible">The statue</supplied> of king Ptolemy, God Philometor, son of Ptolemy and Cleopatra, Gods Epiphaneis 
                <supplied reason="subaudible">was dedicated</supplied>by the city.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p><supplied reason="subaudible">La statua</supplied> del re Tolemeo, Dio Filometore, figlio di Tolemeo e Cleopatra, Dèi Epifani 
                <supplied reason="subaudible">è stata dedicata</supplied> dalla città.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>There are at Ptolemais three similar bases for members of the Lagid family (<ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr033700</ref>, <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr033800</ref> 
                    and this one), which were re-used in a same Roman monument, that seems to lay upon the foundations of a Hellenistic monumental 
                    base to which they probably belonged, perhaps along with a fourth one, now lost. The Roman Square of the Cisterns may have been formerly either the gymnasium 
                    (<bibl><ptr target="#stucchi1975"/>, pp. <citedRange>128, 130</citedRange></bibl>) or the agora (<bibl><ptr target="#laronde1987"/>, p. <citedRange>398</citedRange></bibl>).</p>
                    <p>This base was first thought to mention king Ptolemy VIII Physcon; <bibl><ptr target="#criscuolo2001b"/></bibl> has shown that it was dedicated to Ptolemy VI Philometor,
                        while <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr033800</ref> honoured his younger brother Ptolemy VIII, associated as king with Ptolemy VI and their sister Cleopatra.</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
    </text>
